{
    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix timestamp extraction in IF4p5 ethernet receiver\n\n### Summary\nThe `trx_eth_read_raw_IF4p5` function in the ethernet transport layer was incorrectly setting the timestamp parameter to the packet type field (`sub_type`) instead of extracting the actual timestamp from the `frame_status` field. This caused power control algorithms to receive invalid timestamp values (packet type constants like 0x0020 for IF4p5_PDLFFT), leading to incorrect power calculations and transmission power levels.\n\nThe issue manifested as inconsistent uplink power control behavior and erroneous RSRP measurements during RAU/RRU communication over ethernet interfaces using IF4p5 protocol. The fix extracts proper frame and subframe information from the `frame_status` field and constructs a meaningful timestamp value.\n\n### Changes\n- `radio/ETHERNET/eth_raw.c`: Fixed timestamp extraction in `trx_eth_read_raw_IF4p5` function by reading from `frame_status` field instead of `sub_type`\n- Replaced `*timestamp = test_header->sub_type;` with proper frame/subframe decoding from bits 6-25 of `frame_status`\n- Added explanatory comments for the bit field extraction logic\n\n"
}